team over here,

00:01:04.099 --> 00:01:05.880
doing your-- we
have tasters today.

00:01:05.880 --> 00:01:09.165
So thank you guys for helping
organize everything today.

00:01:09.165 --> 00:01:11.515
So a big hand for them.

00:01:11.515 --> 00:01:12.015
OK.

00:01:12.015 --> 00:01:14.540
So as you know, I've come
out with a brand new book.

00:01:14.540 --> 00:01:16.200
It's called "A Girl
and Her Greens."

00:01:16.200 --> 00:01:19.050
I basically wanted to show
a different side of myself

00:01:19.050 --> 00:01:20.710
from my last book.

00:01:20.710 --> 00:01:22.690
I want to show you my
love of vegetables.

00:01:22.690 --> 00:01:23.750
I love vegetables.

00:01:23.750 --> 00:01:27.580
I grew up eating them
when I was a little girl.

00:01:27.580 --> 00:01:32.120
I was eating peas, carrots,
things like parsnips,

00:01:32.120 --> 00:01:33.870
lots of potatoes, broccoli.

00:01:33.870 --> 00:01:35.940
I loved everything
about broccoli.

00:01:35.940 --> 00:01:37.990
All those kind of
Brassicas I really enjoy.

00:01:37.990 --> 00:01:40.964
And I wanted to show this
off in my book, "A Girl

00:01:40.964 --> 00:01:41.630
and Her Greens."

00:01:41.630 --> 00:01:45.080
So I'm going to make you
two recipes from the book.

00:01:45.080 --> 00:01:47.250
I've got one that I'm
about to show you.

00:01:47.250 --> 00:01:48.489
It's basically a smashed pea.

00:01:48.489 --> 00:01:50.030
It's the best thing
you're ever going

00:01:50.030 --> 00:01:51.212
to eat in your whole life.

00:01:51.212 --> 00:01:52.920
But then you're going
to eat the carrots.

00:01:52.920 --> 00:01:55.190
And they're pretty good, too.

00:01:55.190 --> 00:01:57.430
So basically, just
a thing about peas

00:01:57.430 --> 00:01:59.310
when you go buy
them at the market,

00:01:59.310 --> 00:02:03.000
try and find peas that are not
overstuffed in their shell.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:05.180
So I'm going to pass
you a couple around.

00:02:05.180 --> 00:02:07.930
You can feel these
ones, the bigger ones

00:02:07.930 --> 00:02:10.900
are bursting their
edges a little bit.

00:02:10.900 --> 00:02:12.460
So I'm just going
to open them up.

00:02:12.460 --> 00:02:14.190
And you can see how
they get square.

00:02:14.190 --> 00:02:17.640
Once they start to get square,
they get really starchy.

00:02:17.640 --> 00:02:21.790
So you're looking for peas that
don't have as much-- I don't

00:02:21.790 --> 00:02:23.310
know if you guys can see that.

00:02:23.310 --> 00:02:26.390
They don't have as
much pea to them.

00:02:26.390 --> 00:02:28.430
See how these ones are
all shoved in there.

00:02:28.430 --> 00:02:29.530
They get a bit starchy.

00:02:29.530 --> 00:02:31.260
These are going to
be nice and sweet.

00:02:31.260 --> 00:02:32.920
So I'm going to pass them
around so you can just

00:02:32.920 --> 00:02:33.628
have a long look.

00:02:33.628 --> 00:02:34.400
Do you want to--

00:02:34.400 --> 00:02:35.616
ANDREW: Sure.

00:02:35.616 --> 00:02:36.990
APRIL BLOOMFIELD:
So try and find

00:02:36.990 --> 00:02:39.365
peas that are just a good size.

00:02:39.365 --> 00:02:42.270
And this is basically
an uncooked mushy pea.

00:02:42.270 --> 00:02:44.440
Everybody know what
a mushy pea is?

00:02:44.440 --> 00:02:45.960
Anybody been to England?

00:02:45.960 --> 00:02:46.460
Yeah.

00:02:46.460 --> 00:02:48.730
Have you had fish and
chips with mushy peas?

00:02:48.730 --> 00:02:51.790
They're basically
like long-cooked peas

00:02:51.790 --> 00:02:54.085
that are stewed for--
I don't know, well,

00:02:54.085 --> 00:02:55.577
it depends who's cooking them.

00:02:55.577 --> 00:02:56.410
Could be really bad.

00:02:56.410 --> 00:02:58.035
But they're really
stewed from anywhere

00:02:58.035 --> 00:02:59.850
for like an hour to 25 minutes.

00:02:59.850 --> 00:03:02.930
So in here, I've got some peas.

00:03:02.930 --> 00:03:03.530
It's not many.

00:03:03.530 --> 00:03:04.850
It's probably like a pound.

00:03:04.850 --> 00:03:07.170
A little bit of mint
and some garlic.

00:03:07.170 --> 00:03:09.380
We're basically making a pesto.

00:03:09.380 --> 00:03:09.960
OK.

00:03:09.960 --> 00:03:12.420
And a pesto just means paste.

00:03:12.420 --> 00:03:15.300
So I'm going to add some salt.
This will help flavor the peas.

00:03:15.300 --> 00:03:17.520
They'll bring out
some sweetness.

00:03:17.520 --> 00:03:21.900
I've got some
garlic, mint, salt.

00:03:21.900 --> 00:03:23.935
And I'm just going to
give it a little whiz.

00:03:23.935 --> 00:03:25.060
And you can do it on Pulse.

00:03:25.060 --> 00:03:27.746
And you can either do this
really, really smooth.

00:03:27.746 --> 00:03:29.120
Or you can do it
a little mixture

00:03:29.120 --> 00:03:30.510
of both smooth and chunky.

00:03:30.510 --> 00:03:33.120
It just depends on
personal preference.

00:03:33.120 --> 00:03:36.149
I'm going to make
mine nice and smooth.

00:03:36.149 --> 00:03:37.690
Just give it a little
whiz like this.

00:03:40.950 --> 00:03:41.950
Can you smell that mint?

00:03:41.950 --> 00:03:43.450
I can smell that mint already.

00:03:43.450 --> 00:03:44.585
Smells really springy.

00:03:44.585 --> 00:03:49.390
This is the best thing after
being kind of holed up-- well,

00:03:49.390 --> 00:03:50.980
maybe not in
California-- holed up

00:03:50.980 --> 00:03:53.720
in the winter in New York City,
and there's not a green thing

00:03:53.720 --> 00:03:55.340
around.

00:03:55.340 --> 00:03:57.270
Having these poke up
through the ground

00:03:57.270 --> 00:03:59.650
and seeing them at the
market, I don't know.

00:03:59.650 --> 00:04:03.360
I get really excited
about that kind of stuff.

00:04:03.360 --> 00:04:07.150
So the first thing in spring,
this is the best thing to make.

00:04:07.150 --> 00:04:08.570
In here, I just
put some Pecorino.

00:04:08.570 --> 00:04:09.935
It's a little aged Pecorino.

00:04:09.935 --> 00:04:14.020
So it has a little
complexity to it.

00:04:14.020 --> 00:04:15.970
And so it's a little bit funky.

00:04:15.970 --> 00:04:18.300
So it really just adds
something to the pea.

00:04:18.300 --> 00:04:23.430
It really just elevates
the whole mush.

00:04:23.430 --> 00:04:24.139
It looks good.

00:04:24.139 --> 00:04:26.180
I think I'm going to go
with some olive oil, too.

00:04:26.180 --> 00:04:29.160
Can you guys see this?

00:04:29.160 --> 00:04:30.020
There we are.

00:04:30.020 --> 00:04:31.711
Can you guys see this?

00:04:31.711 --> 00:04:32.210
Yeah.

00:04:32.210 --> 00:04:32.900
OK, good.

00:04:32.900 --> 00:04:35.330
AUDIENCE: Cool.

00:04:35.330 --> 00:04:35.830
Very nice.

00:04:35.830 --> 00:04:36.705
APRIL BLOOMFIELD: OK.

00:04:36.705 --> 00:04:39.403
So then actually, you
could put the olive oil in,

00:04:39.403 --> 00:04:41.100
Or you could just use the bowl.

00:04:41.100 --> 00:04:43.617
But I'm just going to use the
bowl now that I got it off.

00:04:43.617 --> 00:04:45.200
I might not be able
to get it back on,

00:04:45.200 --> 00:04:49.825
so-- They're a bit
temperamental, things things.

00:04:49.825 --> 00:04:51.950
You could do this in a
pestle and mortar, actually.

00:04:51.950 --> 00:04:54.050
It's quite fun.

00:04:54.050 --> 00:04:55.970
Anybody got a pestle
and mortar at home?

00:04:55.970 --> 00:04:56.470
Yeah?

00:04:56.470 --> 00:04:59.390
Just do them in small batches
so your peas don't just

00:04:59.390 --> 00:05:03.211
fly all over the place and
you're trying to catch them.

00:05:03.211 --> 00:05:04.600
A little bit of olive oil.

00:05:07.670 --> 00:05:10.310
That's a lot of olive oil.

00:05:10.310 --> 00:05:11.740
It's still healthier
than butter.

00:05:11.740 --> 00:05:13.800
I mean, come on.

00:05:13.800 --> 00:05:15.320
So just give that
a really good mix.

00:05:15.320 --> 00:05:18.490
And it'll just go a
little wee bit creamy.

00:05:18.490 --> 00:05:20.280
And then now you've
got all that fat.

00:05:20.280 --> 00:05:23.110
You've got a little bit
of the cheese in there.

00:05:23.110 --> 00:05:24.500
It's not too much.

00:05:24.500 --> 00:05:26.974
It's not overpowering
the peas at all.

00:05:26.974 --> 00:05:28.890
You've got some of the
olive oil, again, which

00:05:28.890 --> 00:05:31.300
is slightly more fatty.

00:05:31.300 --> 00:05:32.840
You've got that sweet peas.

00:05:32.840 --> 00:05:35.120
So everything's going to
be quite heavy right now.

00:05:35.120 --> 00:05:37.860
So the way we balance
that out is just

00:05:37.860 --> 00:05:39.050
a little bit of olive oil.

00:05:41.654 --> 00:05:43.320
So we're just going
to add a little bit.

00:05:43.320 --> 00:05:44.695
And we're just
going to taste it.

00:05:47.115 --> 00:05:48.740
AUDIENCE: Are you
separately seasoning?

00:05:48.740 --> 00:05:51.150
Or are you just using the
salt and the Pecorino?

00:05:51.150 --> 00:05:53.460
APRIL BLOOMFIELD: No, I
added a little bit of salt

00:05:53.460 --> 00:05:54.760
in with my bowl.

00:05:54.760 --> 00:05:56.490
Somebody wasn't
paying attention.

00:05:56.490 --> 00:05:59.962
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:59.962 --> 00:06:04.130
I was only-- [LAUGHING]
I'm just kidding.

00:06:04.130 --> 00:06:07.921
Too many nights at Tosca,
that's what it is, yeah.

00:06:07.921 --> 00:06:09.171
AUDIENCE: By the bar upstairs?

00:06:09.171 --> 00:06:10.171
APRIL BLOOMFIELD: Right.

00:06:10.171 --> 00:06:11.052
Yeah, that's right.

00:06:11.052 --> 00:06:12.260
So I'm going to give a taste.

00:06:12.260 --> 00:06:13.930
It's always good to taste.

00:06:13.930 --> 00:06:17.830
So let's just-- it's good.

00:06:20.945 --> 00:06:22.190
It's got some mint in there.

00:06:22.190 --> 00:06:23.390
So it's not too much.

00:06:23.390 --> 00:06:25.260
It's not overtaking the pea.

00:06:25.260 --> 00:06:26.540
It's got a little lemon.

00:06:26.540 --> 00:06:28.520
And so it's really
bright at the beginning.

00:06:28.520 --> 00:06:33.520
But then you get this nice
salty, earthy, clean pea

00:06:33.520 --> 00:06:34.630
flavor.

00:06:34.630 --> 00:06:38.527
And you can see how
creamy it's gone.

00:06:38.527 --> 00:06:39.360
And it's spreadable.

00:06:39.360 --> 00:06:42.330
It's a nice paste.

00:06:42.330 --> 00:06:46.700
So my next job is to do some
bruschetta, which is basically

00:06:46.700 --> 00:06:49.890
just a tasted bread,
usually rubbed

00:06:49.890 --> 00:06:51.990
with a little bit of
garlic and then finished

00:06:51.990 --> 00:06:55.360
with some salt and
some olive oil.

00:06:55.360 --> 00:06:57.780
This is a nice San
Francisco sourdough.

00:06:57.780 --> 00:07:00.920
You guys make the best
bread, San Francisco.

00:07:00.920 --> 00:07:03.700
So you're very lucky.

00:07:03.700 --> 00:07:05.245
So just give it a good old cut.

00:07:08.120 --> 00:07:10.310
Get a nice little piece
for yourself like this.

00:07:10.310 --> 00:07:12.990
And then you can just
pop it on the grill.

00:07:12.990 --> 00:07:15.210
And actually, you can
take this quite far.

00:07:15.210 --> 00:07:17.340
I kind of like that
bitterness that you

00:07:17.340 --> 00:07:20.020
get from a little bit
of the charred bread.

00:07:20.020 --> 00:07:22.370
I think it complements
the sweetness from the pea

00:07:22.370 --> 00:07:24.130
really well.

00:07:24.130 --> 00:07:27.380
For breakfast, if I'm doing
a bit of toast and jam,

00:07:27.380 --> 00:07:29.350
I like to get a bit
more burnt edges on it.

00:07:29.350 --> 00:07:32.060
Because it compliments
that sweetness, too.

00:07:32.060 --> 00:07:33.840
But lots of butter, of course.

00:07:33.840 --> 00:07:35.270
You've got to have your butter.

00:07:35.270 --> 00:07:37.990
So just keep that on there until
it gets all nice and toasty.

00:07:37.990 --> 00:07:40.570
And you want to take
it quite crunchy.

00:07:40.570 --> 00:07:43.590
If you don't, it's just going
to kind of "bloop," drip off.

00:07:43.590 --> 00:07:45.600
And then it's going
to be in your lap.

00:07:45.600 --> 00:07:48.590
And everybody's going to
think you're a lazy eater

00:07:48.590 --> 00:07:50.000
and you have no manners.

00:07:53.130 --> 00:07:54.880
So yeah, just kind
of toast that.

00:07:58.550 --> 00:07:59.555
Let it sit.

00:07:59.555 --> 00:08:02.350
Sometimes it's good to let
things just chill for a second.

00:08:02.350 --> 00:08:05.390
Not 20 minutes, but
just-- and then we'll

00:08:05.390 --> 00:08:06.580
have another little taste.

00:08:06.580 --> 00:08:09.330
So you taste at the beginning,
middle, and the end.

00:08:13.098 --> 00:08:15.315
Did you guys all see those peas?

00:08:15.315 --> 00:08:16.830
Did anybody get to taste?

00:08:16.830 --> 00:08:17.980
Did you taste one?

00:08:17.980 --> 00:08:20.790
You should taste them, too.

00:08:20.790 --> 00:08:23.880
Sometimes they come with
their shells a little bit

00:08:23.880 --> 00:08:25.440
more rough-looking.

00:08:25.440 --> 00:08:26.570
Some are nice and green.

00:08:26.570 --> 00:08:29.370
It doesn't mean that the peas
are any worse inside if they're

00:08:29.370 --> 00:08:34.000
a little bit brown, like this.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:34.650
And taste.

00:08:34.650 --> 00:08:37.960
When you go to the market-- San
Francisco's amazing for this--

00:08:37.960 --> 00:08:41.369
but always make sure
you taste stuff.

00:08:41.369 --> 00:08:42.789
And ask.

00:08:42.789 --> 00:08:46.590
Sometimes you get told off
if you just help yourself.

00:08:46.590 --> 00:08:49.850
I've been told off many times.

00:08:49.850 --> 00:08:51.490
Terrible.

00:08:51.490 --> 00:08:52.740
But always taste.

00:08:52.740 --> 00:08:54.080
Always ask to taste.

00:08:54.080 --> 00:08:55.800
San Francisco's really amazing.

00:08:55.800 --> 00:08:58.610
Because they actually
cut stuff for you.

00:08:58.610 --> 00:08:59.610
They kind of put it out.

00:08:59.610 --> 00:09:01.630
You get your little
toothpick and taste.

00:09:01.630 --> 00:09:03.480
So that's kind of fun.

00:09:03.480 --> 00:09:06.500
And give things a little smell.

00:09:06.500 --> 00:09:07.109
Touch things.

00:09:07.109 --> 00:09:07.900
Have a little look.

00:09:07.900 --> 00:09:08.800
See where they're at.

00:09:08.800 --> 00:09:10.216
Because that's the
only way you're

00:09:10.216 --> 00:09:14.040
going to get more experienced
on picking your vegetables.

00:09:14.040 --> 00:09:16.040
It's just like
buying a bit of fish.

00:09:16.040 --> 00:09:21.390
When you go to a fish market,
you want clear eyes, red gills.

00:09:21.390 --> 00:09:23.360
You want it to
look nice and firm.

00:09:23.360 --> 00:09:26.640
A little bit of slime around
the fish is important.

00:09:26.640 --> 00:09:28.690
It usually means that
it's freshly caught,

00:09:28.690 --> 00:09:31.030
it hasn't been out of
the water very long.

00:09:31.030 --> 00:09:33.320
And if it's
flat-looking, tired--

00:09:33.320 --> 00:09:36.852
it's basically like picking a
handsome man, really, you know.

00:09:36.852 --> 00:09:40.970
It's got to look
pretty sexy, right?

00:09:40.970 --> 00:09:43.290
Or a woman.

00:09:43.290 --> 00:09:46.660
Anyway, so this toast
is pretty much done.

00:09:46.660 --> 00:09:50.870
You see how I got these nice
dark, charred bits on there?

00:09:50.870 --> 00:09:55.470
That's really going to
just elevate this dish.

00:09:55.470 --> 00:09:57.505
Oh, I need a plate to plate.

00:09:57.505 --> 00:09:58.004
Thank you.

00:10:00.760 --> 00:10:02.210
Give it a nice rub of garlic.

00:10:02.210 --> 00:10:04.520
Even though there's a little
bit of garlic in here,

00:10:04.520 --> 00:10:07.150
it's nice to just
layer those flavors.

00:10:07.150 --> 00:10:07.810
Thank you.

00:10:11.050 --> 00:10:12.710
Oh, and a bit of
arugula, please, too.

00:10:12.710 --> 00:10:14.490
Thank you.

00:10:14.490 --> 00:10:16.580
So it's nice to
layer those flavors.

00:10:16.580 --> 00:10:19.470
So this is quite
bulky and thick.

00:10:19.470 --> 00:10:22.880
So I'm just going to give it
a little bit more salt. Again,

00:10:22.880 --> 00:10:26.430
getting all those flavors
layered in is really important.

00:10:26.430 --> 00:10:29.110
And then I'm going to do
a really good, big lashing

00:10:29.110 --> 00:10:31.480
of olive oil on the bread.

00:10:31.480 --> 00:10:33.960
Because again, it's quite bulky.

00:10:33.960 --> 00:10:35.725
You don't want this
dry piece of bread.

00:10:38.584 --> 00:10:39.102
Thank you.

00:10:39.102 --> 00:10:40.060
AUDIENCE: There's that.

00:10:40.060 --> 00:10:41.060
APRIL BLOOMFIELD: Great.

00:10:41.060 --> 00:10:42.030
Thanks.

00:10:42.030 --> 00:10:47.140
And then you just get a good,
healthy scoop of the pea.

00:10:47.140 --> 00:10:49.680
Pop it on the plate like this.

00:10:49.680 --> 00:10:51.816
And then just start
at the round end.

