00:26:26.570 --> 00:26:27.070
All right.

00:26:27.070 --> 00:26:30.190
So I'm going to
save some of these

00:26:30.190 --> 00:26:34.900
like I did just to put
on top as a garnish.

00:26:34.900 --> 00:26:39.730
You could put some fresh basil
in there, too, make it nice.

00:26:39.730 --> 00:26:44.320
Or tarragon, whatever you're
using, chervil, again.

00:26:44.320 --> 00:26:47.930
Just a little bit
more oil and lemon.

00:26:47.930 --> 00:26:50.820
I always do lemon first.

00:26:50.820 --> 00:26:55.870
I think it just helps the oil
not get too greasy on the leaf.

00:26:55.870 --> 00:26:58.197
And so it doesn't
make it as heavy.

00:26:58.197 --> 00:26:59.280
But you could just premix.

00:26:59.280 --> 00:27:03.240
In my "Girl and Her Pig,"
there's a recipe for lemon oil.

00:27:03.240 --> 00:27:08.230
And its 1 to 2, so 1 lemon
to 2 oil, which is nice.

00:27:08.230 --> 00:27:10.500
Just give it a little taste,
a little bit of a season.

00:27:10.500 --> 00:27:15.275
You could premix that and
then just dress it with that.

00:27:15.275 --> 00:27:17.376
Some of this lovely pesto.

00:27:20.617 --> 00:27:24.030
Just pop some of that on top.

00:27:24.030 --> 00:27:24.820
Don't be shy.

00:27:28.010 --> 00:27:31.160
We'll do another
couple of carrots.

00:27:31.160 --> 00:27:35.250
A little bit of this on top.

00:27:35.250 --> 00:27:36.157
These are nice.

00:27:36.157 --> 00:27:37.740
Because they've got
lots of structure.

00:27:37.740 --> 00:27:43.270
So you can just
daintily put them on.

00:27:43.270 --> 00:27:45.510
They don't all have to
be up the right way.

00:27:45.510 --> 00:27:48.402
There could be one
that's upside down.

00:27:48.402 --> 00:27:49.610
Gives it a nice little curve.

00:27:49.610 --> 00:27:52.065
You see that there?

00:27:52.065 --> 00:27:54.670
Nice little curve here.

00:27:54.670 --> 00:27:57.157
Put one here, maybe upside down.

00:27:57.157 --> 00:27:58.990
And then just finish
it with more olive oil.

00:28:02.550 --> 00:28:05.210
And that's basically the
burrata with the carrots.

00:28:05.210 --> 00:28:07.940
So now I'm going to
show you these carrots.

00:28:07.940 --> 00:28:09.464
Hopefully I haven't burned them.

00:28:09.464 --> 00:28:10.630
So this is good.

00:28:10.630 --> 00:28:13.780
We can just throw
them in the oven now.

00:28:13.780 --> 00:28:15.030
Just give them a little shake.

00:28:17.720 --> 00:28:19.570
See the color
you've got on there?

00:28:19.570 --> 00:28:23.320
So now you can just do
these in a medium oven.

00:28:23.320 --> 00:28:26.580
And then you don't have to
worry about getting the color.

00:28:26.580 --> 00:28:28.000
Because you've already done it.

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:30.500
So all you've got to do is just
pay attention to how they're

00:28:30.500 --> 00:28:31.400
cooked.

00:28:31.400 --> 00:28:35.510
And whether they're crunchy
or soft is dependent on you

00:28:35.510 --> 00:28:37.745
and what you like, really.

00:28:37.745 --> 00:28:38.641
A bit more.

00:28:38.641 --> 00:28:39.140
OK.

00:28:39.140 --> 00:28:41.100
And then just throw
them in the oven.

00:28:41.100 --> 00:28:44.066
And these will take
about 10 minutes to cook.

00:28:44.066 --> 00:28:46.440
And again, you can get the
color a little bit more faster

00:28:46.440 --> 00:28:47.470
if you'd like.

00:28:47.470 --> 00:28:50.400
And use a heavy-bottom pan.

00:28:50.400 --> 00:28:54.390
Use a pan that's thick on the
bottom, not like a thin pan.

00:28:54.390 --> 00:28:57.120
Because this'll
help all the sugars.

00:28:57.120 --> 00:28:59.990
Whatever you're cooking, whether
it's searing meat or cooking

00:28:59.990 --> 00:29:04.140
vegetables, it'll bring the
sugars out at a slower rate

00:29:04.140 --> 00:29:05.840
than if you use a thin pan.

00:29:05.840 --> 00:29:07.090
And it's more even.

00:29:07.090 --> 00:29:11.710
So a good pan's really
important to get great food.

00:29:11.710 --> 00:29:12.330
That's it.

